      "ignore": false,
      "order": 10,
      "anno_id": 1,
      "text": " Conversely, if this restriction is induced by a semilinear bijection  $B: X \\to X$ , then  $B$  sends closed hyperplanes of  $X$  to closed hyperplanes which guarantees that  $B$  is a bounded linear or conjugate-linear operator (see [12] or [17, Lemma 3.12]). By [17, Proposition 3.7], A is a scalar multiple of  $(B^{-1})^*$  which is impossible if A is unbounded.",
      "line_with_spans": [
